## 2. SOFT SCORES

### Cover letter specificity — 5 / 5

The opening sentence names the client's two hardest problems (500+ MB parsing,
reconciliation engine) before any self-promotion. The demo link and name appear in
sentence 2 of paragraph 2. The Q1 and Q2 answers are introduced with bold labels
so a skimming client can find them instantly; each answer is code-level (exact
Python API calls, memory numbers, four named isolation layers). The Celery
architecture paragraph (heavy vs light queues, worker_prefetch_multiplier=1) shows
system-design depth. The closing paragraph accepts fixed-price, EU hours, Monday
updates, and probation task without hedging. No filler sentences detected. Word
count is 1,153 (7,174 chars) -- substantive but every paragraph carries new
information.

### Conciseness / skimmability — 4 / 5

The letter earns its length. Q1/Q2 labels help a scanning client find the mandatory
sections. The honest note about the 500 MB browser limitation is short and
well-placed. The Celery paragraph is detailed but directly relevant. Could be
trimmed by 10-15% (the closing paragraph on EUR 4,000 repeats the fixed-price
comfort twice), but nothing is extraneous filler.

### Demo quality — 5 / 5

The demo directly targets the client's Milestone 2 payment gate: a streaming parse
with a live memory-stability chart contrasting iterparse vs naive DOM load. It also
shows 10 reconciliation rules with adjustable thresholds and click-through to
offending source transactions, plus a 100k-row paginated ledger with CSV export.
These three features (parser + memory viz, rules engine, dashboard) map precisely
to the three biggest evaluation criteria in the brief. The honest note in the cover
letter proactively acknowledges that a browser tab cannot stream a real 500 MB file,
framing the demo as a visualization of the exact approach that Milestone 2 will prove
-- a trust-building move rather than a gap.

### Deck polish — 5 / 5

Eight slides, on-brand dark palette (#121118 background, mustard accents, cyan-vivid
secondary). Slides follow a logical arc: problem / live demo CTA / demo proof / Q1
code answer / Q2 four-layer breakdown / 6-milestone roadmap / why Michael / closing
CTA. Demo URL appears on three slides (1, 2, 8). Code block on slide 4 (iterparse)
is a differentiator at this budget tier where most applicants give prose answers.

### Overall persuasiveness — 5 / 5

A client who reads this posting and skips to Q1/Q2 will find exactly what the
posting asks for, answered at a higher technical depth than typical applicants. The
demo then shows the concept working before the client has committed. The package
hits every stated evaluation criterion: large-file experience (Q1), multi-tenant
isolation (Q2), SaaS shipping end-to-end (U.S. Bank + Optum proof points),
test discipline (golden-file reference in cover letter), EU hours, Monday updates,
fixed-price comfort, and probation task acceptance. The honest stub note is a
signal of professional calibre.

**Soft score average: 4.8 / 5.0**

