## 3. ADDITIONAL OBSERVATIONS

### Strengths

- The Q1 answer is the strongest differentiator in this package. lxml.etree.iterparse
  with elem.clear() and ancestor pruning, with concrete memory numbers (80-120 MB vs
  600-800 MB), is exactly the answer a senior engineer writes. Most applicants say
  "streaming" without specifics. The memory chart demo makes this tangible.

- The Q2 four-layer answer (JWT, SQLAlchemy session, PostgreSQL RLS with SET LOCAL,
  API isolation tests) is technically precise. The PgBouncer SET LOCAL caveat (vs
  SET SESSION) shows operational depth. This level of specificity at EUR 4,000 is
  uncommon.

- The honest note about the demo's browser limitation is proactively placed and
  well-framed. It turns a potential objection into a trust signal.

- The package's internal consistency is strong: the demo's memory chart and rules
  engine support the Q1/Q2 answers, which are repeated in the deck slides, which are
  also summarized in the one-pager QA blocks.

### Minor notes (not blockers)

- The cover letter is long (1,153 words). Some Upwork clients do not read past the
  first screen. The Q1/Q2 bold labels help navigation, but if the client paste-area
  truncates, the closing paragraph (EUR 4,000 acceptance) might fall off. Consider
  moving the EUR acceptance up or surfacing it in a bullet if pasting to Upwork.

- proposalDeckUrl and proposalPageUrl are null in workSamples.js (deck and one-pager
  are local files, not yet at public URLs). This is expected per proposal-writer.out
  and does not affect the demo URL or the work-sample card rendering.

- Live URL verification is pending merge to main. The GH Pages deploy takes 1-2
  minutes post-push. Confirm the demo loads before submitting the Upwork proposal.

